# Module 3 — Method References ⭐⭐⭐⭐

## 1. What is Method Reference?

A **Method Reference** is a shorter and cleaner way of writing a lambda expression when the lambda simply calls an existing method.

Instead of writing:

```java
name -> System.out.println(name)
```

You can write:

```java
System.out::println
```

The `::` operator is called the **method reference operator**.

---

## 2. Why was it introduced?

Before Java 8

```java
Collections.sort(list, new Comparator<String>() {
    @Override
    public int compare(String a, String b) {
        return a.compareTo(b);
    }
});
```

Java 8 Lambda

```java
Collections.sort(list, (a, b) -> a.compareTo(b));
```

Method Reference

```java
Collections.sort(list, String::compareTo);
```

Each step reduces unnecessary code while keeping the same behavior.

---

# 3. Problem it solves

Without Method Reference

```java
list.forEach(name -> System.out.println(name));
```

The lambda isn't doing any extra work—it simply calls an existing method.

Method Reference

```java
list.forEach(System.out::println);
```

Cleaner.

More readable.

Less code.

---

# 4. Internal Working

Consider:

```java
list.forEach(System.out::println);
```

`forEach()` expects a `Consumer<T>`.

Consumer has:

```java
void accept(T t);
```

Java internally converts

```java
System.out::println
```

into

```java
name -> System.out.println(name)
```

The compiler matches:

```
Consumer.accept(name)
↓

System.out.println(name)
```

So Method Reference is simply **syntactic sugar** for a compatible lambda.

---

# 5. Syntax

General syntax

```java
ClassName::methodName
```

or

```java
object::methodName
```

or

```java
ClassName::new
```

---

# Types of Method References

There are **4 types**.

Interviewers usually ask for all four.

| Type                                 | Example               |
| ------------------------------------ | --------------------- |
| Static Method                        | Class::staticMethod   |
| Instance Method of Particular Object | object::method        |
| Instance Method of Arbitrary Object  | Class::instanceMethod |
| Constructor Reference                | Class::new            |

---

# Type 1 — Static Method Reference ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Example

```java
class MathUtil {

    static int square(int x) {
        return x * x;
    }

}
```

Lambda

```java
Function<Integer, Integer> f =
        x -> MathUtil.square(x);
```

Method Reference

```java
Function<Integer, Integer> f =
        MathUtil::square;
```

Calling

```java
System.out.println(f.apply(5));
```

Output

```
25
```

---

### How Java Executes It

When

```java
f.apply(5)
```

is called

Compiler internally does

```
MathUtil.square(5)
```

Memory Flow

```
Function.apply(5)

↓

MathUtil.square(5)

↓

returns 25
```

---

# Another Example

```java
class Demo {

    static void greet(String name) {
        System.out.println("Hello " + name);
    }

}
```

Lambda

```java
Consumer<String> c =
        name -> Demo.greet(name);
```

Method Reference

```java
Consumer<String> c =
        Demo::greet;
```

Output

```
Hello John
```

