# Type 2 — Instance Method Reference of Particular Object ⭐⭐⭐⭐

Suppose

```java
class Printer {

    void print(String s) {
        System.out.println(s);
    }

}
```

Create object

```java
Printer p = new Printer();
```

Lambda

```java
Consumer<String> c =
        s -> p.print(s);
```

Method Reference

```java
Consumer<String> c =
        p::print;
```

Call

```java
c.accept("Java");
```

Output

```
Java
```

---

### Internal Working

Compiler converts

```java
p::print
```

into

```java
s -> p.print(s)
```

---

# Type 3 — Instance Method Reference of Arbitrary Object ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

This confuses almost everyone initially.

Suppose

```java
List<String> list =
        Arrays.asList("Dog", "Cat", "Apple");
```

Sorting

Lambda

```java
list.sort((a, b) -> a.compareTo(b));
```

Method Reference

```java
list.sort(String::compareTo);
```

People ask:

> Where is the object?

Java creates it automatically.

When sorting,

```
compare(a,b)
```

becomes

```
a.compareTo(b)
```

Compiler understands

```
String::compareTo

↓

first parameter becomes object

↓

second parameter becomes argument
```

So

```
(a,b)->a.compareTo(b)
```

is equivalent to

```
String::compareTo
```

---

### Another Example

Convert to lowercase

Lambda

```java
list.stream()
    .map(s -> s.toLowerCase());
```

Method Reference

```java
list.stream()
    .map(String::toLowerCase);
```

Internally

```
String::toLowerCase

↓

s -> s.toLowerCase()
```

---

# Type 4 — Constructor Reference ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Instead of calling constructor manually.

Class

```java
class Employee {

    Employee() {
        System.out.println("Created");
    }

}
```

Lambda

```java
Supplier<Employee> s =
        () -> new Employee();
```

Method Reference

```java
Supplier<Employee> s =
        Employee::new;
```

Call

```java
Employee e = s.get();
```

Output

```
Created
```

---

Another example

```java
Function<String, Employee> f =
        Employee::new;
```

Constructor

```java
Employee(String name)
```

Calling

```java
Employee e = f.apply("John");
```

Internally

```
new Employee("John")
```

---

# Memory / Execution Flow

Suppose

```java
list.forEach(System.out::println);
```

Flow

```
ArrayList

↓

Stream

↓

forEach()

↓

Consumer.accept(item)

↓

System.out.println(item)

↓

Console
```

Method Reference does **not** create a new method or object. It simply points to an existing method that matches the functional interface.

